1
00:00:04,891 --> 00:00:11,278
So I thought this evening to talk a little bit about the third noble truth, the cessation of dukkha.

2
00:00:11,298 --> 00:00:21,350
And from the Vipassana guidelines that we were reading there, the very last is some description of this, the goal of our path, the cessation of suffering, nibbana.

3
00:00:22,871 --> 00:00:34,746
And it goes, there is the unborn, the undying, the uncreated, the unconditioned, refuge, harbour, home, perfect contentment and peace.

4
00:00:37,661 --> 00:00:39,905
So it's just interesting to reflect on that.

5
00:00:39,926 --> 00:00:46,877
I mean, there are some beautiful analogies, refuge, harbour, home, perfect contentment and peace.

6
00:00:46,896 --> 00:00:50,942
But then, of course, there's the unborn, the undone, the uncreated, the unconditioned.

7
00:00:50,963 --> 00:00:53,707
That can just stir confusion to some extent.

8
00:00:54,027 --> 00:00:55,130
What does that all mean?

9
00:00:55,170 --> 00:01:03,703
So I think the main thing is just to be aware of what any reflections of Nibbana actually bring up in you.

10
00:01:04,072 --> 00:01:11,278
You know, just let the reflection of Nibbāna bring up whatever it brings up, whether it's peace and inspiration, whether it's confusion and frustration.

11
00:01:12,140 --> 00:01:22,671
Just allow that to be recognized, to be noted, and that then we're on the path to Nibbāna, and we'll find out eventually what it actually all is about.

12
00:01:22,691 --> 00:01:30,618
So in the main, the Buddha didn't speak much about Nibbāna, but just the path to Nibbāna.

13
00:01:31,948 --> 00:01:43,867
And that's our focus too, to really work out how do we stop suffering rather than spend a lot of time trying to work out what is it that we're aiming for?

14
00:01:44,027 --> 00:01:45,209
What exactly is it?

15
00:01:45,709 --> 00:01:46,990
What is the unconditioned?

16
00:01:51,498 --> 00:01:58,968
However, there is some value in also spending some time trying to clarify what the goal is.

17
00:01:59,658 --> 00:02:04,697
So Joseph Goldstein, for example, just uses the analogy of walking through the woods at night.

18
00:02:04,718 --> 00:02:09,515
So he wanted to get through the woods at night to get to his home.

19
00:02:10,306 --> 00:02:23,882
So the fact that he knew that his home was in that direction, that gave him the motivation, the stimulus, the energy, the wish to walk through the woods.

20
00:02:24,864 --> 00:02:31,230
So he could stop and reflect on that in order to get through the woods if he got a bit dejected.

21
00:02:32,332 --> 00:02:38,439
But if he was just to kind of look ahead and try to see his house at the other side of the woods, then he'd probably stumble.

22
00:02:38,875 --> 00:02:42,759
and fall and just, you know, just cause myself trouble.

23
00:02:43,330 --> 00:02:51,556
So in the same way we can stop every now and again and just maybe reflect on Nibbana for some energy, for some stimulus to our path.

24
00:02:52,078 --> 00:02:57,742
But the main task is then to let go of all that and just this moment.

25
00:02:57,883 --> 00:03:00,705
So like him looking down at his feet, take this step safely.

26
00:03:01,406 --> 00:03:11,294
So we let go of the possible future, whatever it is, and we come back to the here and now and let our practice lead us to Nibbana.

27
00:03:15,628 --> 00:03:31,307
And I think one way we can gain confidence that Nibana is actually a very worthy goal is that as we do our practice, we do see how it brings out the best in us and how it lets go of some level of stress and suffering in our lives.

28
00:03:31,989 --> 00:03:36,895
So we can more and more trust that where we're going is actually a very, very worthy place.

29
00:03:40,502 --> 00:03:43,467
So some words the Buddha did use to describe it.

30
00:03:43,486 --> 00:03:44,747
One was the end of dukkha.

31
00:03:45,049 --> 00:03:52,897
That's the most common description maybe of Nibbāna, the end of all sense of dissatisfaction or stress or suffering of any kind.

32
00:03:53,818 --> 00:03:56,582
So dukkha does not apply there.

33
00:03:57,804 --> 00:04:02,729
He called it unshakable bliss and another term was everlasting.

34
00:04:04,060 --> 00:04:09,467
So in that sense, everlasting, we see that transience doesn't apply, anicca doesn't apply.

35
00:04:09,507 --> 00:04:17,899
So nirvana isn't a changing state, like everything changing in this universe, and that keeps slipping through our fingers.

36
00:04:17,978 --> 00:04:20,723
Nirvana is unchanging, everlasting.

37
00:04:23,887 --> 00:04:31,096
So dukkha and anicca do not apply, but that third characteristic that we've talked about, anatta or not-self,

38
00:04:31,802 --> 00:04:37,009
It's arguable, and scholars do argue, but a lot of them would say that anatta does apply.

39
00:04:37,050 --> 00:04:47,324
So anatta does apply to nirvana, in the sense that if there's a self, we're always trying to control things and manipulate things and hold them to ourselves.

40
00:04:48,086 --> 00:04:51,730
So whenever we get to nirvana, we won't be able to hold it for ourself.

41
00:04:52,372 --> 00:04:54,295
There'd be no wish even to hold it for ourself.

42
00:04:55,817 --> 00:04:59,262
It's not graspable, and we won't even want to grasp at it.

43
00:05:00,372 --> 00:05:07,918
So the self brings about boundaries and limits and defensiveness and everything like that.

44
00:05:08,660 --> 00:05:11,002
So Nibbana is without boundary, without limit.

45
00:05:12,223 --> 00:05:20,290
So in that sense, and one way the Buddha described it is, he said, Nibbana exists, but not the one who enters it.

46
00:05:21,531 --> 00:05:24,413
Which is a nice way to put it.

47
00:05:24,494 --> 00:05:28,016
Nibbana exists, but not the one who enters it.

48
00:05:31,507 --> 00:05:33,370
So again, something to reflect on.

49
00:05:33,432 --> 00:05:40,809
Another way of stating that would be that nirvana is the reality of non-grasping.

50
00:05:42,492 --> 00:05:46,040
As we said, the self gets created to grasp onto some desire.

51
00:05:47,223 --> 00:05:49,649
That's happening all through our lives.

52
00:05:50,439 --> 00:06:01,697
Something pleasant stimulates our senses and we feel the desire and then a sense of self gets created in order to grasp onto that and try to hold it and make it mine.

53
00:06:01,716 --> 00:06:08,447
So our practice is always to relax, to let go as much as we can.

54
00:06:08,466 --> 00:06:12,312
And we can get little moments ourselves.

55
00:06:12,512 --> 00:06:15,697
We can tune in to little, you could call them temporary nirvanas.

56
00:06:15,718 --> 00:06:19,062
We can get tastes of the state of not grasping.

57
00:06:19,415 --> 00:06:20,817
When a desire fades away.

58
00:06:21,478 --> 00:06:28,528
It's a very subtle moment, so we don't always tune into it, but it's really worthwhile beginning to tune in to that sense of the ending of a desire.

59
00:06:28,569 --> 00:06:33,237
You might notice there's actually no sense of me or mine at that moment.

60
00:06:33,697 --> 00:06:35,000
There isn't a sense of stress.

61
00:06:35,060 --> 00:06:37,103
There isn't a sense of anything to defend.

62
00:06:39,007 --> 00:06:44,533
So it really is worth beginning to tune in to these little moments, very momentary.

63
00:06:45,052 --> 00:06:50,237
So we often just don't notice them at all and let the next desire come up very quickly.

64
00:06:50,257 --> 00:06:56,504
But the more we tune in and notice them, we'll be so interested in them that the next desire won't maybe come up quite so quickly.

65
00:06:59,927 --> 00:07:04,692
So every time desire fades, we do get a little momentary taste of the piece of manna.

66
00:07:10,427 --> 00:07:12,350
Now, it's a very quiet happiness.

67
00:07:13,153 --> 00:07:14,714
It doesn't call our attention.

68
00:07:14,735 --> 00:07:15,976
I think that's why we miss it.

69
00:07:16,798 --> 00:07:19,483
You know, we said those who are mindful are in the presence of Nirvana.

70
00:07:19,502 --> 00:07:23,108
So Nirvana is always present, but we actually just don't notice it.

71
00:07:23,149 --> 00:07:24,190
We don't tune into it.

72
00:07:26,334 --> 00:07:28,158
And that's really because it is so subtle.

73
00:07:28,177 --> 00:07:33,887
It's so quiet that our minds are designed really to tune into drama.

74
00:07:34,423 --> 00:07:38,848
As we've been talking about, you know, for survival, we need to find out where the danger is.

75
00:07:38,949 --> 00:07:41,172
We need to find out where the good stuff is for survival.

76
00:07:41,692 --> 00:07:49,762
So our minds are attuned to the dramatic, the loud, the colorful, you know, the difficult.

77
00:07:50,704 --> 00:07:56,870
And our minds don't naturally tune into what's unobtrusive, what's quiet, what's not a threat.

78
00:07:57,543 --> 00:08:12,170
So it takes a lot of practice for us to begin to sense that little non-obtrusive, non-dramatic moments where there's no big storyline going on, there's nothing to take home out of this, you know, there's no big success on offer to us.

79
00:08:13,353 --> 00:08:16,218
So that those moments are actually really worth tuning into.

80
00:08:16,259 --> 00:08:18,742
We have to kind of persuade ourselves of that, I think.

81
00:08:19,124 --> 00:08:20,225
We're so...

82
00:08:20,644 --> 00:08:29,038
goal-orientated, you know, we want spiritual progress and we have a sense that there will be, you know, a big cheer when we get to Nirvana.

83
00:08:29,798 --> 00:08:32,042
And, yeah, there'll be great delight and everything.

84
00:08:32,062 --> 00:08:40,053
That, you know, the fact of the quiet, subtle, non-obtrusive little moments

85
00:08:40,894 --> 00:08:49,710
It doesn't stimulate us in our culture to be looking for something unobtrusive, something you can't say anything about, something you can't tell your friends much about.

86
00:08:49,730 --> 00:08:57,162
It's not like a prize that we tend to value in our culture, quietness and subtlety.

87
00:08:58,543 --> 00:09:07,458
So we really have to train ourselves to tune into quietness, to actually feel the value of it, to feel the immense peace that's on offer.

88
00:09:13,075 --> 00:09:16,960
And in those very quiet and unobtrusive moments, the mind easily wanders.

89
00:09:17,020 --> 00:09:23,028
That's what I've always found, is that we begin to lose interest as we get closer and closer to that kind of quietness.

90
00:09:23,889 --> 00:09:26,133
The mind starts making up all kinds of little stories.

91
00:09:26,634 --> 00:09:30,359
It's funny, it nearly goes delirious sometimes.

92
00:09:30,580 --> 00:09:32,863
It just makes up stories about anything and everything.

93
00:09:33,604 --> 00:09:36,748
So again, we just have to be patient with all of that.

94
00:09:36,768 --> 00:09:42,897
It's just our minds not recognising value and going into some sort of a...

95
00:09:43,687 --> 00:09:45,710
A spin, a spin.

96
00:09:45,769 --> 00:09:58,488
Now the Buddha did describe Nibbana as subtle and at first he thought this state is so subtle that nobody, he didn't think anybody else in the world could actually pick up on it.

97
00:09:58,508 --> 00:10:00,049
He wasn't going to teach at first.

98
00:10:01,412 --> 00:10:03,115
So anyway we have to have a lot of patience.

99
00:10:03,174 --> 00:10:10,284
It does take time for subtlety to persuade us of its value and to even persuade us that it's there.

100
00:10:11,158 --> 00:10:17,756
I remember one teacher saying that the first time that she really noticed calm, her noting word had a little question mark on it.

101
00:10:17,817 --> 00:10:20,684
It was, you know, calm, calm.

102
00:10:20,705 --> 00:10:23,373
She couldn't believe that there was calmness, you know.

103
00:10:23,754 --> 00:10:25,759
We really can disbelieve.

104
00:10:26,363 --> 00:10:30,187
and not trust and deny calmness.

105
00:10:30,467 --> 00:10:32,410
Possibly we're embarrassed because it's always been there.

106
00:10:33,010 --> 00:10:35,995
So there's something in our mind that says, oh my God, I've been overlooking something.

107
00:10:36,336 --> 00:10:39,178
So there's all that embarrassment about having made a mistake.

108
00:10:39,700 --> 00:10:42,844
So we screen out the calmness that is always there.

109
00:10:42,984 --> 00:10:52,235
So there'll be all kinds of obstacles to noticing calm and subtlety, but the more we tune in, the more we'll have some sense of the goal of the path and the value of it.

110
00:10:55,404 --> 00:11:01,292
Now, when the Buddha was talking about this world and Nibbāna, he often used the analogy of fire.

111
00:11:01,972 --> 00:11:09,422
So fire for this world of what's called samsara, you know, the opposite of Nibbāna.

112
00:11:09,442 --> 00:11:13,226
This world we live in, where is the round of, you know, greed, hatred, delusion.

113
00:11:14,268 --> 00:11:22,518
And then fire going out is often the analogy for Nibbāna, that moment when fire is extinguished.

114
00:11:23,938 --> 00:11:24,399
And

115
00:11:24,734 --> 00:11:29,197
The word nirvana is actually used, I think even commonly in India today, for cooling.

116
00:11:29,698 --> 00:11:31,681
You know, people say, will you nirvana the rice?

117
00:11:31,701 --> 00:11:33,783
So it's a cooling term.

118
00:11:34,923 --> 00:11:39,008
You know, we have such lovely weather here this week that we can have a sense of the value of cooling.

119
00:11:39,408 --> 00:11:41,971
You know, in our culture, sometimes cooling might not seem so great.

120
00:11:41,990 --> 00:11:46,274
But in India, obviously, with their very hot climate, cooling is greatly valued.

121
00:11:46,394 --> 00:11:51,179
And fire, on the other hand, is aggressive, oppressive, threatening.

122
00:11:53,168 --> 00:12:02,601
So we have a sense of this world as oppressive, threatening, horrid, and then the ending of all of that, the relief when a fire goes out.

123
00:12:06,508 --> 00:12:12,437
When the Buddha was enlightened, one quotation is that he surveyed the world with the eye of an awakened one.

124
00:12:13,378 --> 00:12:21,149
As he did so, he saw living beings burning with the many fevers and aflame with the many fires born of passion, aversion and delusions.

125
00:12:23,745 --> 00:12:27,971
So there's that sense that we are actually burning in our own fevers.

126
00:12:29,134 --> 00:12:31,697
We're burning in our own passions and aversion and delusion.

127
00:12:33,320 --> 00:12:40,169
In the culture of India at the time, fire was thought to be trapped by its own fuel.

128
00:12:41,371 --> 00:12:44,356
So fire has to stay in the one place.

129
00:12:44,557 --> 00:12:45,619
It has to be a wood fire.

130
00:12:45,678 --> 00:12:48,623
It's trapped by the wood until the wood is all burnt out.

131
00:12:49,226 --> 00:12:55,133
It can be trapped by other things, grass and so on, and it's trapped there until the fuel is all burnt out.

132
00:12:58,417 --> 00:13:03,741
And in our case, then, the fuel is sense pleasure, you know, wanting all the lovely stuff.

133
00:13:04,883 --> 00:13:06,865
And then views and opinions.

134
00:13:07,505 --> 00:13:14,913
We are very addicted to our views and opinions as well, you know, how we love to be right and...

135
00:13:15,669 --> 00:13:17,673
persuade others of our views and so on.

136
00:13:17,693 --> 00:13:26,172
So that's one of the fuels for keeping us here in samsara is our very tight beliefs.

137
00:13:26,753 --> 00:13:31,884
And often we are quite afraid to examine our deepest beliefs and that would include the belief in self.

138
00:13:32,745 --> 00:13:34,590
You know, that's a hard one for us to examine.

139
00:13:40,020 --> 00:13:49,390
Now again, in India at the time of the Buddha, once the fuel was exhausted and the fire went out, the understanding was that the fire then was freed.

140
00:13:50,972 --> 00:13:56,357
And it existed then in a latent form, hidden but extending throughout the universe.

141
00:13:58,880 --> 00:14:09,032
So that's some sort of an analogy for us of the enlightened mind, the awakened mind, existing in a latent form, hidden but extending throughout the universe.

142
00:14:10,192 --> 00:14:16,783
So it's no longer in that stage bound to its fuel and unbinding is another term for an abana.

143
00:14:17,865 --> 00:14:27,341
And just a quotation relevant to that, at the death of the Buddha himself, one of his disciples, Aniruddha says, like a flame going out was the liberation of awareness.

144
00:14:28,755 --> 00:14:31,337
So the fire is freed.

145
00:14:31,698 --> 00:14:33,600
As the flame goes out, the fire is freed.

146
00:14:34,601 --> 00:14:35,422
We can't see it.

147
00:14:36,623 --> 00:14:39,625
We can't access it anymore ourselves directly.

148
00:14:40,047 --> 00:14:43,470
But the belief is that it's hidden and extending throughout the universe.

149
00:14:45,991 --> 00:14:50,616
So we have no way of knowing its whereabouts or quantifying it in any way.

150
00:14:50,736 --> 00:14:53,720
It's beyond our measuring, our reckoning.

151
00:14:54,760 --> 00:14:58,323
So questions like, does the Buddha exist after death, just can't be answered.

152
00:14:58,506 --> 00:15:02,932
Because the Buddha's existence or non-existence after death is indescribable in our terms.

153
00:15:04,034 --> 00:15:07,860
So there's a conversation between the Buddha and Upasava about this.

154
00:15:08,520 --> 00:15:14,188
Upasava is trying to get the Buddha to say, does the awakened person exist after death?

155
00:15:15,370 --> 00:15:17,874
He says, there is nothing by which you can measure him.

156
00:15:18,855 --> 00:15:22,259
That by which he can be talked about is no longer there for him.

157
00:15:24,342 --> 00:15:26,285
You cannot say that he does not exist.

158
00:15:28,881 --> 00:15:35,149
When all ways of being, all phenomena are removed, all ways of description have also been removed.

159
00:15:38,634 --> 00:15:44,961
So we have that mystery that it's not describable in our phenomenology.

160
00:15:47,183 --> 00:15:48,846
So that's probably a good point to end.

161
00:15:48,885 --> 00:15:50,288
Nirvana is beyond description.

162
00:15:50,649 --> 00:15:56,816
But just going back to the Joseph Goldstein analogy then of walking through the woods at night.

163
00:15:56,875 --> 00:15:58,298
So

164
00:15:58,597 --> 00:16:01,341
you know, to reflect on Nibbana can be useful.

165
00:16:03,924 --> 00:16:05,527
And it's worth asking, how do you feel?

166
00:16:05,567 --> 00:16:07,409
You know, I often ask myself that.

167
00:16:07,429 --> 00:16:13,398
How do I feel when I reflect on these kind of mysterious sayings?

168
00:16:13,878 --> 00:16:28,538
And often it does bring up hindrances because, you know, the wish to know a little bit better, for me, you know, might bring me into dullness or aversion of some description.

169
00:16:28,837 --> 00:16:33,297
You know, the fact that this can't be actually put into words can be frustrating and so on.

170
00:16:33,934 --> 00:16:41,702
So, um, obviously it's the path I just, uh, bear with all of those hindrances, just let them burn out.

171
00:16:41,763 --> 00:16:51,511
But what I always find is that once they have burned out, there's some new level of awareness where I'm seeing more beautiful qualities that little bit clearer.

172
00:16:52,273 --> 00:16:55,436
It could be peaceful sensations in the body.

173
00:16:55,495 --> 00:17:01,302
It could be emotions of say, kindness that I just hadn't really been able to access before.

174
00:17:01,341 --> 00:17:02,743
So,

175
00:17:04,478 --> 00:17:12,349
I think the reflection on nirvana, no matter what it brings up, just allowing ourselves to sit with that will bring us towards nirvana.

176
00:17:12,769 --> 00:17:14,692
So I think that's a good point at which to end.

177
00:17:17,798 --> 00:17:27,271
So we'll just sit for a while.

178
00:17:27,291 --> 00:17:27,853
Thank you.

